{"id":"1904.03364","submitter":"David Hernandez","authors":"David M. Hernandez (Harvard-Smithsonian CfA, RIKEN)","title":"Improving the accuracy of simulated chaotic $N$-body orbits using\n  smoothness","comments":"9 pages, 8 figures. Matches accepted MNRAS version","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1093/mnras/stz2662","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.EP astro-ph.CO astro-ph.GA astro-ph.IM","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Symplectic integrators are a foundation to the study of dynamical $N$-body\nphenomena, at scales ranging from from planetary to cosmological. These\nintegrators preserve the Poincar\\'e invariants of Hamiltonian dynamics. The\n$N$-body Hamiltonian has another, perhaps overlooked, symmetry: it is smooth,\nor, in other words, it has infinite differentiability class order (DCO) for\nparticle separations greater than $0$. Popular symplectic integrators, such as\nhybrid methods or block adaptive stepping methods do not come from smooth\nHamiltonians and it is perhaps unclear whether they should. We investigate the\nimportance of this symmetry by considering hybrid integrators, whose DCO can be\ntuned easily. Hybrid methods are smooth, except at a finite number of phase\nspace points. We study chaotic planetary orbits in a test considered by Wisdom.\nWe find that increasing smoothness, at negligible extra computational cost in\nparticular tests, improves the Jacobi constant error of the orbits by about $5$\norders of magnitude in long-term simulations. The results from this work\nsuggest that smoothness of the $N$-body Hamiltonian is a property worth\npreserving in simulations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 6 Apr 2019 05:33:13 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 19 Sep 2019 00:17:48 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-10-09"}
